Title: The Tell-Tale Heart
Credit: Screenplay adaptation of
Author: Edgar Allan Poe's short story (1843, public domain)
Draft date: 7/18/2026
Notes: Monologue-heavy formatting test -- single narrator, minimal cast.

====

FADE IN:

INT. OLD HOUSE - NARRATOR'S ROOM - NIGHT

Total darkness but for a single candle. The NARRATOR (age and gender unspecified, gaunt, wide-eyed) addresses camera directly, unnervingly calm.

NARRATOR
True! Nervous, very, very dreadfully nervous I had been and am, but why will you say that I am mad? The disease had sharpened my senses, not destroyed, not dulled them.

(beat)

Above all was the sense of hearing acute. I heard all things in the heaven and in the earth. I heard many things in hell. How, then, am I mad? Hearken, and observe how healthily, how calmly, I can tell you the whole story.

CUT TO:

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (RECURRING, SEVEN NIGHTS)

Pitch dark. The Narrator opens a door with agonizing slowness, a lantern held shut so no light escapes, over the course of a full hour, night after night.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
It took me an hour to place my whole head within the opening so far that I could see him as he lay upon his bed. Ha! Would a madman have been so wise as this?

The OLD MAN sleeps undisturbed, an eye -- pale blue, filmed like a vulture's -- closed beneath a wrinkled lid.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
It was not the old man who vexed me, but his Evil Eye. Whenever it fell upon me, my blood ran cold, and so, by degrees, I made up my mind to take the life of the old man, and thus rid myself of the eye forever.

Six nights pass this way -- the Narrator entering, watching, retreating without acting, the eye always closed, always spared.

CUT TO:

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (THE EIGHTH NIGHT)

The Narrator opens the door as before -- more cautiously than ever, smiling at their own cunning. The lantern-ray, thin as a spider's thread, finally falls directly upon the open vulture eye.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
I had my head in, and was about to open the lantern, when my thumb slipped, and the old man sprang up in bed, crying out, "Who's there?"

The Old Man sits rigid in the dark, listening, terrified without knowing why -- a groan escapes him, the sound of mortal terror.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
I knew the sound well. Many a night, just at midnight, when all the world slept, it has welled up from my own bosom, deepening with its dreadful echo the terrors that distracted me.

The lantern ray finds the open eye at last -- and with it, the Narrator hears something else.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
(faster, breathless)
I heard it -- a low, dull, quick sound, such as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton. It was the beating of the old man's heart.

The sound grows louder in the silence, unbearable.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
It increased my fury, as the beating of a drum stimulates the soldier into courage. And now a new anxiety seized me -- the sound would be heard by a neighbor!

The Narrator RUSHES forward. A brief, violent struggle in the dark. Silence.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
(calmer now)
His eye would trouble me no more.

CUT TO:

INT. OLD MAN'S BEDROOM - NIGHT (CONTINUOUS)

By lantern light, methodical and precise, the Narrator dismembers the body and conceals it beneath the floorboards, replacing each plank with exacting care.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
If still you think me mad, you will think so no longer when I describe the wise precautions I took for the concealment of the body. There was nothing to wash out -- no stain of any kind -- no blood-spot whatever.

A clock strikes four. Three sharp knocks sound at the street door below.

CUT TO:

INT. OLD MAN'S HOUSE - FRONT ROOM - CONTINUOUS

The Narrator, entirely composed, admits three POLICE OFFICERS.

NARRATOR
(smiling, at ease)
The shriek, I said, was my own in a dream. The old man, I mentioned, was absent in the country.

The Narrator leads them through the house, even into the very bedroom, and finally sets chairs directly atop the boards concealing the body, inviting the officers to rest.

FIRST OFFICER
(settling in, relaxed)
A quiet night, on the whole.

The officers chat easily among themselves. The Narrator answers cheerfully at first -- then falls gradually silent.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
My head ached, and I fancied a ringing in my ears, but still they sat and still chatted. The ringing became more distinct -- a low, dull, quick sound, much such a sound as a watch makes when enveloped in cotton.

The Narrator's composure begins to fracture -- pacing, sweating, talking too loudly to drown out a sound only they can hear, growing louder by the second.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Was it possible they heard not? Almighty God! No, no! They heard! They suspected! They knew! They were making a mockery of my horror!

The officers continue their pleasant conversation, entirely unaware, smiling.

NARRATOR (V.O.) (CONT'D)
Anything was more tolerable than this derision! I felt that I must scream or die, and now -- again -- hark! Louder! Louder! Louder!

The Narrator SNAPS.

NARRATOR (CONT'D)
(shrieking, to the officers)
Villains! Dissemble no more! I admit the deed! Tear up the planks! Here, here! It is the beating of his hideous heart!

Blackout.

FADE OUT.

> THE END <
